      "content": [
        {
          "anchor": "Discussion",
          "level": 2,
          "text": "Discussion",
          "type": "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "text": "You add an activity to a context by calling the ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.classkit/documentation/ClassKit/CLSContext/createNewActivity()",
              "isActive": true,
              "type": "reference"
            },
            {
              "text": " method when the user makes a new attempt at a task. You then use the context’s ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.classkit/documentation/ClassKit/CLSContext/currentActivity",
              "isActive": true,
              "type": "reference"
            },
            {
              "text": " property to access the newly created activity. If the context has an existing activity from a previous attempt, it ceases to be available to your app as a result of creating a new one. However, the network still retains its data for reporting purposes.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "text": "Don’t store a reference to the current activity. Always use the ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.classkit/documentation/ClassKit/CLSContext/currentActivity",
              "isActive": true,
              "type": "reference"
            },
            {
              "text": " property to get it. The object returned to you might change from time to time because of network synchronization, even when the underlying task is the same.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        }
      ],
      "kind": "content"
    }
  ],
